moves.1. Nf3: Reti. I intend on the Fianchetto at this point, but what I like about f3 is there are so many options. I've learned this is probably not a good opening when I'm playing a more advanced player.
moves.2. g3: I have had some success against 1300-1400 level players when I Fianchetto and that is still my plan. I prefer flank attacks.
moves.2... d5 3. d4 e6 4. e3: In hindsight, I think Bg2 may have been better here. I deviated from my initial plan. I'm now a move behind that plan. In addition, my DSB is not happy.
moves.4... Bd6 5. Bg2: A little late. I wanted to castle first!
moves.5... O-O 6. O-O c5: 4. e3 is still not that useful. Seems like I wasted a move and I don't think black will forgive.
moves.7. Nc3: Developing minor pieces. I would like to advance my knights quickly here since the center seems so complicated.
moves.7... Nc6 8. Nb5 Be7 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5: That's ugly. Two pieces unprotected. I think advancing the knight to b5 was premature. I considered Nd6, but that doesn't look very healthy.
moves.10... Nd7 11. e4: Trying to free up my DSB, still paying for that e3 move. I thought black would trade pawns.
moves.11... d4: Rut Roh, that can't be good.
moves.12. Nd6: I reconsidered the knight move. I thought I might get a chance to protect the e5 pawn with my DSB. I should've moved f4.
moves.13. Nxc8: I thought a bishop might be worth more than a knight. In hindsight, maybe the other bishop, but black's LSB is not really worth the trade.
moves.13... Rxc8 14. f4 Nc6 15. Bd2 c4 16. c3: From here, I made so many errors (beyond what I've already made), I've also decided to stop annotating. Good game.

opening: Reti (A05), King's Indian attack, Spassky's variation
